Hereâ€™s an example of API documentation for a fictional RESTful API called BookStore API. This example demonstrates how to structure and present API documentation effectively.

BookStore API Documentation
Base URL
https://api.bookstore.com/v1


Authentication

Type: Bearer Token
Header:Authorization: Bearer <your_token>


Obtain the token by logging in via the /auth/login endpoint.


Endpoints
1. Get All Books


URL: /books


Method: GET


Description: Retrieves a list of all books in the store.


Headers:

Authorization: Bearer Token (required)



Query Parameters:

Response:

Status Code: 200 OK
Body:Json{
  "data": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "title": "The Great Gatsby",
      "author": "F. Scott Fitzgerald",
      "price": 10.99
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "title": "1984",
      "author": "George Orwell",
      "price": 8.99
    }
  ],
  "pagination": {
    "page": 1,
    "limit": 10,
    "total": 50
  }
}






2. Add a New Book

URL: /books
Method: POST
Description: Adds a new book to the store.
Headers:

Authorization: Bearer Token (required)
Content-Type: application/json


Body:Json{
  "title": "To Kill a Mockingbird",
  "author": "Harper Lee",
  "price": 12.99
}


Response:

Status Code: 201 Created
Body:Json{
  "id": 3,
  "title": "To Kill a Mockingbird",
  "author": "Harper Lee",
  "price": 12.99
}






3. Delete a Book


URL: /books/{id}


Method: DELETE


Description: Deletes a book by its ID.


Headers:

Authorization: Bearer Token (required)



Path Parameters:



Parameter
Type
Required
Description




id
int
Yes
ID of the book.





Response:

Status Code: 204 No Content




This structure includes endpoint descriptions, parameters, headers, example requests, and responses, making it easy for developers to integrate with the API.
